Not quite. In your original program, the Wait function is *technically* occurring after the conditional, but because the conditional is false when Scratch isn't touching the goblin it was constantly waiting for one second. So when Scratch *does* touch the goblin, the code had to finish the Wait function to get back to the conditional statement

In other words, let's imagine the code was:
```When Green Flag Clicked
    Forever
    {
      If Windak says "Hello."
      { 
       Say "Hello"
      }
      Sip Coffee
    }```
I'll keep sipping coffee until you say "hello" to me because the Sip Coffee function is after the conditional. But:

```When Green Flag Clicked
    Forever
    {
      If Windak says "Hello."
      { 
       Say "Hello"
       Sip Coffee
      }
    }```

If the Sip Coffee function is in the conditional, I'll only sip my coffee if you say "Hello"

